                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-date&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;comment-link&quot; href=&quot;#comment3538411_2533348&quot;&gt;&lt;span title=&quot;2010-08-03 23:04:35Z, License: CC BY-SA 2.5&quot; class=&quot;relativetime-clean&quot;&gt;Aug 3, 2010 at 23:04&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;The big problem with keeping your own database is keeping it updated.  Olson and Windows are maintained for you.  I&apos;ve had more than one case of having bad DST transitions because tables were out of date.  Ripping them out entirely and relying on a framework or OS level database is much more reliable.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;/users/634824/matt-johnson-pint&quot; title=&quot;215,731 reputation&quot; class=&quot;comment-user&quot;&gt;Matt Johnson-Pint&lt;/a&gt;
